# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-e-class
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] An **automatic transmission** (**AT**) or **automatic gearbox** is a multi-speed transmission used in motor vehicles that does not require any input from the driver other than throttle position to change forward gears under normal driving conditions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first true automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first mass-produced automatic transmission was General Motors' Hydra-Matic, introduced in Oldsmobile models for the 1940 model year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions are especially prevalent in vehicular drivetrains, particularly those subject to intense mechanical acceleration and frequent idle/transient operating conditions; commonly commercial/passenger/utility vehicles, such as buses and waste collection vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Vehicles with internal combustion engines, unlike electric vehicles, require the engine to operate in a narrow range of rates of rotation, requiring a gearbox, operated manually or automatically, to drive the wheels over a wide range of speeds.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Globally, 43% of new cars produced in 2015 were manual transmissions, falling to 37% by 2020.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have long been prevalent in the United States, but only started to become common in Europe much later.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In Europe in 1997, only 10–12% of cars had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In 1957 over 80% of new cars in the United States had automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Automatic transmissions have been standard in large cars since at least 1974.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] By 2020 only 2.4% of new cars had manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Historically, automatic transmissions were less efficient, but lower fuel prices in the US made this less of a problem than in Europe.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In the United Kingdom, a majority of new cars have had automatic transmissions since 2020.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Several manufacturers including Mercedes and Volvo no longer sell cars with manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The growing prevalence of automatic transmissions is attributed to the increasing number of electric and hybrid cars, and the ease of integrating it with safety systems such as Autonomous Emergency Braking.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The efficiency (power output as a percentage of input) of conventional automatic transmissions ranges from 86 to 94%.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Manual transmissions are more fuel efficient than all but the newest automatic transmissions due to their inherently low parasitic losses (typically of about 4%) in addition to being cheaper to make, lighter, better performing, and of simpler mechanical design.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Fuel economy worsens with lower efficiency.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] However, manual transmissions require the driver to operate the clutch and change gear whenever required.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Real-world tests reported in 2022 found that in typical driving manual transmissions achieved 2 to 5% better fuel economy than automatics, increasing to 20% with an expert driver.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Some laboratory tests show automatics in a better light due to the tests using a prescribed shifting pattern for manuals not always optimized for economy.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] However, on long highway journeys manual transmissions require maintaining a very specific cruising speed to optimise economy, making automatics preferable.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The most common design of automatic transmissions is the hydraulic automatic, which typically uses planetary gearsets that are operated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The transmission is connected to the engine via a torque converter (or a fluid coupling prior to the 1960s), instead of the friction clutch used by most manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A hydraulic automatic transmission uses planetary gearsets instead of the manual transmission's design of gears lined up along input, output and intermediate shafts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] To change gears, the hydraulic automatic uses a combination of internal clutches, friction bands or brake packs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These devices are used to lock certain gears, thus setting which gear ratio is in use at a given time.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A sprag clutch (a ratchet-like device which can freewheel and transmits torque in only one direction) is often used for routine gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The advantage of a sprag clutch is that it eliminates the sensitivity of timing a simultaneous clutch release/apply on two planetary gearsets, simply "taking up" the drivetrain load when actuated, and releasing automatically when the next gear's sprag clutch assumes the torque transfer.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The friction bands are often used for manually selected gears (such as low range or reverse) and operate on the planetary drum's circumference.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Bands are not applied when the drive/overdrive range is selected, the torque being transmitted by the sprag clutches instead.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The aforementioned friction bands and clutches are controlled using automatic transmission fluid (ATF), which is pressurized by a pump and then directed to the appropriate bands/clutches to obtain the required gear ratio.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The ATF provides lubrication, corrosion prevention, and a hydraulic medium to transmit the power required to operate the transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Made from petroleum with various refinements and additives, ATF is one of the few parts of the automatic transmission that needs routine service as the vehicle ages.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The *main pump* which pressurises the ATF is typically a gear pump mounted between the torque converter and the planetary gear set.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The input for the main pump is connected to the torque converter housing, which in turn is bolted to the engine's flexplate, so the pump provides pressure whenever the engine is running.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The pressure of the ATF is regulated by a *governor* connected to the output shaft, which varies the pressure depending on the vehicle speed.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The *valve body* inside the transmission is responsible for directing hydraulic pressure to the appropriate bands and clutches.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] It receives pressurized fluid from the main pump and consists of several spring-loaded valves, check balls, and servo pistons.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In older automatic transmissions, the valves use the pump pressure and the pressure from a centrifugal governor on the output side (as well as other inputs, such as throttle position or the driver locking out the higher gears) to control which ratio is selected.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle and engine change speed, the difference between the pressures changes, causing different sets of valves to open and close.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In more recent automatic transmissions, the valves are controlled by solenoids.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These solenoids are computer-controlled, with the gear selection decided by a dedicated transmission control unit (TCU) or sometimes this function is integrated into the engine control unit (ECU).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Modern designs have replaced the centrifugal governor with an electronic speed sensor that is used as an input to the TCU or ECU.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Modern transmissions also factor in the amount of load on an engine at any given time, which is determined from either the throttle position or the amount of intake manifold vacuum.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The multitude of parts, along with the complex design of the valve body, originally made hydraulic automatic transmissions much more expensive and time-consuming to build and repair than manual transmissions; however mass-production and developments over time have reduced this cost gap.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] To provide coupling and decoupling of the engine, a modern automatic transmission uses a torque converter instead of the friction clutch used in a manual transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The 1904 Sturtevant "horseless carriage gearbox" is often considered to be the first automatic transmission for motor vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] At higher engine speeds, high gear was engaged.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] As the vehicle slowed down and engine speed decreased, the gearbox would shift back to low.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] However, the transmission was prone to sudden failure, due to the transmission being unable to withstand forces from the abrupt gear changes.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The adoption of planetary gearsets was a significant advance towards the modern automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] One of the first transmissions to use this design was the manual transmission fitted to the 1901–1904 Wilson-Pilcher automobile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This transmission was built in the United Kingdom and used two epicyclic gears to provide four gear ratios.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A foot clutch was used for standing starts, gear selection was using a hand lever, helical gears were used (to reduce noise) and the gears used a constant-mesh design.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A planetary gearset was also used in the 1908 Ford Model T, which was fitted with a two-speed manual transmission (without helical gears).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] An early patent for the automatic transmission was granted to Canadian inventor Alfred Horner Munro of Regina in 1923.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Being a steam engineer, Munro designed his device to use compressed air rather than hydraulic fluid, and so it lacked power and never found commercial application.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In 1923, a patent was approved in the United States describing the operation of a transmission where the manual shifting of gears and manual operation of a clutch was eliminated.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Hoffman from Chicago and was titled: *Automatic Gear Shift and Speed Control*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] However, it would be over a decade later until automatic transmissions were produced in significant quantities.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In the meantime, several European and British manufacturers would use preselector gearboxes, a form of manual transmission which removed the reliance on the driver's skill to achieve smooth gear shifts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission using hydraulic fluid was developed in 1932 by two Brazilian engineers, José Braz Araripe and Fernando Lehly Lemos.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The evolution towards mass-produced automatic transmissions continued with the 1933–1935 REO Motor Car Company *Self-Shifter* semi-automatic transmission, which automatically shifted between two forward gears in the "Forward" mode (or between two shorter gear ratios in the "Emergency low" mode).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Driver involvement was still required during normal driving, since standing starts required the driver to use the clutch pedal.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This was followed in 1937 by the Oldsmobile *Automatic Safety Transmission*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Similar in operation to the REO *Self-Shifter*, the *Automatic Safety Transmission* shifted automatically between the two gear ratios available in the "Low" and "High" ranges and the clutch pedal was required for standing starts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The Chrysler *Fluid Drive*, introduced in 1939, was an optional addition to manual transmissions where a fluid coupling (similar to a torque-convertor, but without the torque multiplication) was added, to avoid the need to operate a manual clutch.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The General Motors Hydra-Matic became the first mass-produced automatic transmission following its introduction in 1939 (1940 model year).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Available as an option in cars such as the Oldsmobile Series 60 and Cadillac Sixty Special, the Hydra-Matic combined a fluid coupling with three hydraulically controlled planetary gearsets to produce four forward speeds plus reverse.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The transmission was sensitive to engine throttle position and road speed, producing fully automatic up- and down-shifting that varied according to operating conditions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] During World War II, the Hydra-Matic was used in some military vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first automatic transmission to use a torque converter (instead of a fluid coupling) was the Buick Dynaflow, which was introduced for the 1948 model year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In normal driving, the Dynaflow used only the top gear, relying on the torque multiplication of the torque convertor at lower speeds.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The Dynaflow was followed by the Packard Ultramatic in mid-1949 and the Chevrolet Powerglide for the 1950 model year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Each of these transmissions had only two forward speeds, relying on the converter for additional torque multiplication.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In the early 1950s, BorgWarner developed a series of three-speed torque converter automatics for car manufacturers such as American Motors, Ford and Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Chrysler was late in developing its own true automatic, introducing the two-speed torque converter PowerFlite in 1953, and the three-speed TorqueFlite in 1956.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The latter was the first to utilize the Simpson compound planetary gearset.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In 1956, the General Motors Hydra-Matic (which still used a fluid coupling) was redesigned based around the use of two fluid couplings to provide smoother shifts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This transmission was called the *Controlled Coupling Hydra-Matic*, or "Jetaway" transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The original Hydra-Matic remained in production until the mid-1960s at GM, with the licensed Rolls-Royce Automatic transmission soldiering on until 1978 on the Rolls-Royce Phantom VI.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In 1964, General Motors released a new transmission, the Turbo Hydramatic, a three-speed transmission which used a torque convertor.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The Turbo Hydramatic was among the first to have the basic gear selections (*park*, *reverse*, *neutral*, *drive*, *low*) which became the standard gear selection used for several decades.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] By the late 1960s, most of the fluid-coupling two-speed and four-speed transmissions had disappeared in favor of three-speed units with torque converters.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Also around this time, whale oil was removed from the automatic transmission fluid.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] During the 1980s, automatic transmissions with four gear ratios became increasingly common, and many were equipped with lock-up torque convertors in order to improve fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Electronics began to be more commonly used to control the transmission, replacing mechanical control methods such as spring-loaded valves in the valve body.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Most systems use solenoids which are controlled by either the engine control unit, or a separate transmission control unit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This allows for more precise control of shift points, shift quality, lower shift times and manual control.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first five-speed automatic was the Jatco 5R01, introduced in 1989 by Nissan in the Cedric and Gloria, and was electronically controlled.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first six-speed automatic was the ZF 6HP26 transmission, which debuted in the 2002 BMW 7 Series (E65).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first seven-speed automatic was the Mercedes-Benz 7G-Tronic transmission, which debuted a year later.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In 2007, the first eight-speed transmission to reach production was the Toyota AA80E transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first nine-speed and ten-speed transmissions were the 2013 ZF 9HP transmission and 2017 *Toyota Direct Shift-10A* (used in the Lexus LC) respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The gear selector is the input by which the driver selects the operating mode of an automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A few automobiles employed a lever on the instrument panel, such as the 1955 Chrysler Corporation cars, and notably, the Corvair.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Some automatic transmissions, especially by General Motors from 1940 to 1964, used a layout with *reverse* as the bottom position (e.g.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Many transmissions also include positions to restrict the gear selection to the lower gears and engages the engine brake.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These positions are often labelled "L" (low gear), "S" (second gear) or the number of the highest gear used in that position (eg 3, 2 or 1).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] If these positions are engaged at a time when it would result in excessive engine speed, many modern transmissions disregard the selector position and remain in the higher gear.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Many modern transmissions include modes to adjust the shift logic to prefer either power or fuel economy.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] "Sport" (also called "Power" or "Performance") modes cause gear shifts to occur at higher engine speeds, allowing higher acceleration.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] "Economy" (also called "Eco" or "Comfort") modes cause gear shifts to occur at lower engine speeds to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Since the 1990s, systems to manually request a specific gear or an upshift/downshift have become more common.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These *manumatic* transmissions offer the driver greater control over the gear selection that the traditional modes to restrict the transmission to the lower gears.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Use of the manumatic functions are typically achieved either via paddles located beside the steering column, or "+" and "-" controls on the gear selector.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Some cars offer drivers both methods to request a manual gear selection.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A *continuously variable transmission* (CVT) can change seamlessly through a continuous (infinite) range of gear ratios, compared with other automatic transmissions that provide a limited number of gear ratios in fixed steps.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The flexibility of a CVT with suitable control may allow the engine to operate at a constant angular velocity while the vehicle moves at varying speeds.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] CVTs are used in cars, tractors, UTVs, motor scooters, snowmobiles, and earthmoving equipment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The most common type of CVT uses two pulleys connected by a belt or chain.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] However, several other designs have also been used.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] A *dual-clutch transmission* (DCT, sometimes referred to as a *twin-clutch transmission*, or *double-clutch transmission*) uses two separate clutches for odd and even gear sets.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The design is often similar to two separate manual transmissions with their respective clutches contained within one housing, and working as one unit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] In most car and truck applications, the DCT functions as an automatic transmission, requiring no driver input to change gears.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first DCT to reach production was the *Easidrive* automatic transmission introduced on the 1961 *Hillman Minx* mid-size car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This was followed by various eastern European tractors through the 1970s (using manual operation via a single clutch pedal), then the *Porsche 962 C* racing car in 1985.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first DCT of the modern era was used in the 2003 *Volkswagen Golf R32*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Since the late 2000s, DCTs have become increasingly widespread, and have supplanted hydraulic automatic transmissions in various models of cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Modern versions of these systems that are fully automatic in operation, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, require no driver input over gear changes or clutch operation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Semi-automatic versions require only partial driver input (i.e., the driver must change gears manually), while fully automatic versions require no manual driver input, whatsoever (TCU or ECU operates both the clutch system and gear shifts automatically).
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Modern automated manual transmissions (AMT) have their roots and origins in older clutchless manual transmissions that began to appear on mass-production automobiles in the early 1930s and 1940s, prior to the introduction of hydraulic automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These systems were designed to reduce the amount of clutch or gear shifter usage required by the driver.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] These devices were intended to reduce the difficulty of operating conventional unsynchronised manual transmissions ("crash gearboxes") that were commonly used at the time, especially in stop-start driving.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] An early example of this transmission was introduced with the Hudson Commodore in 1942, called *Drive-Master*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Another early example of this transmission system was introduced in the 1955 Citroën DS, which used a 4-speed *BVH* transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This semi-automatic transmission used an automated clutch, which was actuated using hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Gear selection also used hydraulics, however, the gear ratio needs to be manually selected by the driver.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] This system was nicknamed *Citro-Matic* in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] The first modern AMTs were introduced by BMW and Ferrari in 1997, with their *SMG* and *F1* transmissions, respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Both systems used hydraulic actuators and electrical solenoids, and a designated transmission control unit (TCU) for the clutch and shifting, plus steering wheel-mounted paddle shifters, if the driver wanted to change gear manually.
[src:chrysler-e-class/automatic-transmission] Modern fully automatic AMTs, such as *Selespeed* and *Easytronic*, have now been largely superseded and replaced by the increasingly widespread dual-clutch transmission design.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The first Buick Century debuted as the Series 60 then renamed in 1936 as a shorter and lighter model featuring the same engine as the bigger Roadmaster and Limited series giving it more performance while using the shorter wheelbase body of the Buick Special.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] During the 1930s and 1940s it was Buick's companion to the top level Roadmaster and was offered as a 2-door and 4-door sedan and convertible.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century name was used on six generations of cars of varying sizes as well as performance and trim levels.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1969, Buick developed a concept car known as the Century Cruiser.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In the 1970s, the Century Regal became a separate model and market positioning between the two products changed from year to year depending on sales.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century was updated to front wheel drive in 1982 and was Buick's 2-door coupe, 4-door sedan and station wagon, with regular updates and feature upgrades as customer preferences changed over time.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Originally, the Series 60 had the 331.4 cu in (5.4 L) OHV Buick Straight-6 engine from the Series 70, developing 99 bhp (74 kW) at 2,800 rpm.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] It had, at the beginning of the generation, a full-length running board denoting the top model for Buick at the time, shared with the short wheelbase, entry level Series 40.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The bodystyles available were torpedo, sedan, coupe, and roadster convertible, using GM's "B-body" platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Starting with this generation, all GM cars shared a corporate appearance as a result of the "Art and Colour Section" headed by Harley J.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Earl and modest yearly changes were introduced to freshen the appearance.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1931, the running board was reduced and the OHV 220.7 cu in (3.6 L) Buick Straight-8 engine was introduced that developed 90 bhp (67 kW).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Aesthetically, the Series 60 remained almost unchanged, and the same fact occurred also in the following year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1933, the length of the body increased and the radiator was now concealed behind a façade with a grille.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The engine power increased to 97 hp (72 kW), and 1933 was the first year all GM vehicles were installed with optional vent windows which were initially called “No Draft Individually Controlled Ventilation” later renamed "Ventiplanes".
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1934, the appearance was changed to a more rounded appearance, with a new OHV 278 cu in (4.6 L) eight-cylinder engine and 100 hp.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1935, the model remained almost unchanged while the body style selections were similar to larger Buicks but more affordably priced.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Six choices were available to include both 2- and 4-door convertibles using the term "phaeton" for the 4-door convertible with a listed price of US$1,675 ($39,334 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1936, the model changed its name to "Century".
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Buick renamed its entire model lineup for the 1936 model year to celebrate the engineering improvements and design advancements over their 1935 models, introducing a "streamlined" appearance.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Buick's Series 40 model range became the Special, the Series 60 became the Century, the Series 80 became the Roadmaster, and the Series 90, Buick's longest and most luxurious vehicles, became the Limited.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The terminology "Series 60" and "Series 70" were shared with Cadillac, while "Series 60", "Series 70", "Series 80" and "Series 90" were shared with Oldsmobile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The basic formula for the 1936 to 1942 Century was established by mating the shorter wheelbase Special bodies to the Roadmaster's larger displacement straight-eight engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century offered four different types of 2-door body styles to include convertibles and only one 4-door Sedan, with the ratio remaining coupes over sedans until 1938 when there were three coupe and three sedan choices.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 1940 Series 50 Super combined the longer Roadmaster body with the smaller displacement Special engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Prices listed for the 2-door Victoria Coupe started at US$1,055 ($24,478 in 2025 dollars ) to US$1,135 ($26,271 in 2025 dollars ) for the 2-door Convertible.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century was discontinued at the end of the abbreviated 1942 model year due to World War II, when production of passenger vehicles stopped on February 4, 1942, during which total model production only accounted for about 10% of Buick's total output.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Buick reintroduced the Century using the same formula of mating the smaller, lighter Buick Special body to its largest and most powerful 322 cu in (5.3 L) "Fireball" OHV V8 engine mated with a Dynaflow automatic transmission, with the intent of giving Buick a performance vehicle.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Included in the model lineup during this period was a station wagon model, a body style that had been unavailable during the Century's first production period of 1936 until 1942.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1953 *The Buick-Berle Show* introduced product placement commercials on TV, and later in 1955 *The Honeymooners* was one of the sponsors.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Introduced in the middle of the 1955 model year, the four-door Buick Century Riviera along with the four-door Special Riviera, the four-door Oldsmobile 98 Holiday, and four-door 88 Holiday, were the first four-door hardtops ever produced.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For the first time, the Century was repositioned below the C-body Buick Super and priced lower.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] It continued to feature four "VentiPorts" on the front fenders like the larger Buick Roadmaster indicating its status equal to the Super, denoting it was a junior level Buick using the shorter B-body.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] It also introduced the "Panoramic" one-piece wrap around windshield on all GM cars for 1955.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1955, the California Highway Patrol placed a large fleet order for 270 Century two-door sedans, a body style unavailable to the general public.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] It combined the Special two-door sedan body shell with Century powertrain, of which 135 were Dynaflow automatics and 135 were manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Broderick Crawford was shown driving a two-door Century sedan during the first season of his popular syndicated TV series *Highway Patrol*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] These Century two-door sedans were actual police vehicles owned by the California Highway Patrol and were loaned to the TV production company, the CHP door emblems were changed to a generic highway patrol emblem.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] (In later seasons, he drove a four-door Century but these were not California Highway Patrol owned vehicles.) Power brakes were optional.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Power windows were standard in the convertible.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1957, Buick styling was notable for its three-piece rear window design.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] This was a feature in all series fixed-roof body-styles, (excluding wagons and convertibles).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Because the Century was considered the senior "small Buick", the model received a version of GM's hardtop station wagon, the **Century Caballero Estate** for the 1957 and 1958 model years and was not continued for 1959.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1959, Buick renamed the Century the Invicta.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Buick Century nameplate was revived for the 1973 model year on the rear-wheel drive intermediate A-body platform, which was redesigned for this year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The name replaced Skylark for Buick's mid-sized cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The **Century Regal** coupe was added at the top of the model range and later became a separate series, dropping the Century name for 1976.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] It was available with two- and four-barrel versions of the Buick 350, putting out 150 and 175 hp (112 and 130 kW), respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 225 horsepower (168 kW) 455 was also an option.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The base Century and Century 350 coupes had a fastback roof with large rear quarter glass, while the Century Luxus featured a more formal notchback roofline with narrow opera windows.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century Estate replaced the Buick Sport Wagon.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] By replacing the Skylark, the Century inherited the Gran Sport performance option.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The package was available with any engine and included upgraded suspension, additional instrumentation, and unique appearance treatment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Dual exhaust increased output of the four-barrel 350 to 190 hp (142 kW).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] While the Stage I 455 was somewhat diminished from its performance heyday due to emission controls, output was competitive for the era at 270 hp (201 kW) and 390 lb⋅ft (529 N⋅m).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A Saginaw three-speed manual was standard with either 350 engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A Muncie M-21 four-speed was available with either 350 or with the regular 455, while the Stage I required a Turbo-Hydramatic 400.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 1974 Buick Century and Regal were introduced with HEI (High-Energy Ignition systems) instead of points and ignition coil.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 1974 Buick Century Gran Sport was still, "Available only as a Hardtop Colonnade Coupe, it carries the Rallye ride and handling suspension with stabilizer bars, front and rear.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Plus a specialized blacked-out grille and head lamp doors, an accent stripe on the rear deck, special tail lamps and Gran Sport grille ornamentation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1975, the Luxus was renamed Century Custom.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The new 110 hp (82 kW) 231 V6 was installed as standard equipment along with a three-speed manual transmission on coupes and sedans, and the big-block 455 was no longer available.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The four-barrel 350 V8 became standard on station wagons.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A new landau top became available for fastback coupes that partially covered the rear quarter glass, giving an appearance similar to the formal-roof Century Custom.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A Century Special coupe was added to the lineup, using the fastback roofline.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Special was marketed as an economy variant of the Century and was only available with the V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1975, the US government legalized rectangular headlights and Buick added them to the Century for the 1976 model year, positioned side-by-side on coupes, and stacked vertically on sedans.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Sedans received a taller, more-formal grille, while coupes got an angled, body-colored front end along with new bodyside sheet metal that lacked the traditional "sweepspear".
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Gran Sport option was discontinued with the 455 engines and only 231 V6 or 350 V8 were available on the last 1,288 made vehicles merely with appearance and suspension option package.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Buick Centuries were used in the 1975 and 1976 Indianapolis Motor Speedway as pace cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Buick introduced a 1975 Buick Century "Free Spirit" edition replica based on the Indy Pace Car for the public with patriotic graphic decals and the Buick Hawk on the hood.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] This 1975 vehicle had a transmission shifter on the floor with bucket seats and "Hurst Hatch" T-tops installed.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The white exterior and blue/white interior were based on the 1975 two-door sheet metal.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The engine was a 350 V8, as opposed to the 455 V8 used on the actual Indy 500 Pace Car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Alternatively, in 1976, Buick introduced the "Free Spirit" edition of the Indy Pace Car; it was received the 1976 Century Special's facelifted sheet metal with the 231 V6 engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The original Indy Pace Car had the turbocharged 231 V6.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The replica featured a silver, black, and red paint with a black interior.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The vehicle included a positive-traction differential.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1977, the V6 engine was revised to be even-firing, and a 403 cu in (6.6 L) Oldsmobile V8 was added as an option for station wagons.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] GM downsized its intermediate line, reducing wheelbase by 4 in (102 mm) and curb weight by nearly half a ton.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century was initially offered as an "aeroback" fastback two-door coupe and a fastback four-door sedan along with a station wagon model (sharing bodies with the Oldsmobile Cutlass Salon).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The car was over a foot shorter, several inches narrower, and several hundred pounds lighter than its predecessor.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Big-block engines were discontinued and the new base powerplant was Buick's new 196 cu in (3.2 L) V6 introduced specifically for the Century and Regal.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 231 cu in (3.8 L) V6 and the Chevrolet 305 V8 were options.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Pontiac 265 cu in (4.3 L) and 301 cu in (4.9 L) replaced the Chevrolet engine for 1979.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] One of the more rare models of this time was the 1979 to 1980 Century Turbo Coupe, powered by a turbocharged version of the 3.8 L V6, which offered V8-like performance with more reasonable fuel consumption and reduced emissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Turbo Coupe was not nearly as popular as the similar Regal Turbo Sport Coupe of the time, and total production is estimated to be less than 2,500.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The two fastback models (along with the Oldsmobile Cutlass Salon) proved unpopular.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1980, the fastback four-door sedan was dropped in favor of a conventional notchback four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] After 1980, the Century fastback coupe was discontinued.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] With the introduction of the new front-wheel drive Century in 1982, the existing notchback sedan and wagon models were transferred to the Regal line.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In January 1982, GM debuted the downsized fifth-generation Century, using the front-wheel drive A platform, in coupe and sedan forms.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The fifth-generation Century shared the A platform with the Cutlass Ciera, Pontiac 6000 and Chevrolet Celebrity.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Together the A-bodies became some of GM's most transparent examples of badge engineering, which was highlighted on the cover of the August 22, 1983 issue of *Fortune* magazine as examples of near-uniformity, embarrassing the company and prompting GM to recommit to design leadership.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In October 1983, a station wagon was added to the lineup to replace the discontinued Regal wagon.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 1984 model year also had an Olympic version of the Buick Century, commemorating the 1984 games in Los Angeles, California.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1985, all 1986 versions were "freshened" with a new, more angular front fascia.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Both four-cylinder gasoline units and diesel V6 engines were offered in this generation, although neither became popular.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Performance versions of several Buick models, including the Century coupe, were marketed in the mid-1980s under the T-Type name.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] With Buick's 181 cu in (3.0 L) V6 producing 110 hp (82 kW), the Century T-Type's performance was modest, but the Buick 3.8 V6 SFI engine, producing 140–150 hp (104–112 kW), offered passable performance in this comparatively lightweight vehicle.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1985 and 1986, Hess & Eisenhardt/Car Craft of Lima, Ohio converted 124 finished Buick Century coupes into coachbuilt convertibles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Although these convertibles were sold as new cars through Buick dealerships, these conversions were not factory authorized.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In 1986, the engine distributor was replaced by a coil-pack ignition system that proved to be far more reliable than the system that it replaced.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The "Chevrolet Century" were sold in South America and the Caribbean.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In Mexico, it was sold as the Century Limited (with no brand, although it wears the Buick logos).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Introduced for 1984, it was the top model for General Motors Mexico, and it survived the import car wave from 1991 (previously new car importations were forbidden in Mexico) and continued in production until the 1996 model year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In Japan it was sold as the Buick Regal because of the Toyota Century limousine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century received a facelift in late 1988 for the 1989 model year, gaining a new more-rounded roofline, but continuing on the A-body platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Black plastic inserts with the Buick tri-shield emblem replaced the rear quarter windows.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The front end received flush headlamps and a rounded grille, and the stand-up hood ornament was now standard.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] All sedan models were easily distinguished by their full-width taillights that followed a Buick tradition of big taillights.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 3300 was introduced in 1989 as a replacement for the 3800 cc engine, offering an increase of 10 horsepower, but a loss of 15 lb-ft of torque.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The smaller engine featured multiport fuel injection, waste spark distributor-less ignition controlled by the ECM after startup, but had no balance shaft.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] An interior refresh came in 1989 for 1990 models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The 1989 model had seatbelts mounted on the b-pillar, for 1990-1996 the seatbelts were mounted on the door.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] From 1989 to 1992, the Century had a black bumper and side trim, and from 1993 to 1996 the Century had a bodycolored trim.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Originally, the Century, as with the rest of the A-body range, was intended to be phased out in 1990 in favor of the more modern W-body line of midsized cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] However, the Century (and its sister car, the Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera) continued to remain popular nearing the intended end of their production runs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Thus, it was decided that the older Century and Cutlass Ciera would instead continue production as lower priced alternatives to their proposed replacements, the Regal and Cutlass Supreme respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For the 1991 model year, the Century received another slight facelift featuring a bigger radiator grille and different headlamps.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The interior featured new door panels with the window switches and door lock switches relocated to a more convenient configuration found on more modern cars, where the switch location corresponds with the window location in the car body.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] This feature never appeared on its sibling the Oldsmobile Ciera, which retained the inline switch bank mounted flush with the door panel, the rear switch being the driver's door window.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century windows switches were not backlit, but illuminated by a small bulb in the door panel trim above the switch bank.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Other interior changes included new seat covers, and relocating the front outboard seat belts from the A-pillar into the door, functioning as "automatic" seat belts so that the belts could be buckled and the door opened and closed while still buckled.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The driver and front passenger could enter and exit the vehicle while the seat belt was still fastened.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1993, the 2.5 L inline-four was replaced with a new, 115 hp (86 kW), 2.2-liter four.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 1994, the slow-selling coupe model was dropped (603 had been sold for 1993, equivalent to 0.5% of overall Century sales), and all models received a standard driver's-side airbag.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Also in 1993, the 160 hp (119 kW) 3.3 L Buick V6 was replaced with a 3.1 L V6 with the same power rating, and power on the 2.2 L four was up to 120 hp (89 kW) with the introduction of MFI.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Midway through the 1994 model year, a round speedometer replaced the wide rectangular one, but the car still carried on with the original dash.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Despite its dated design, the Century and its sibling the Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera still sold well during the 1990s and proved both reliable and profitable to GM since their tooling costs had been monetized.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For the 1997 model year, Buick released the sixth-generation Century (in December 1996, nearly 15 years after its last redesign).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Joining the newly redesigned Regal on the W-body chassis, the Century continued its image of traditional entry-level luxury.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] While sharing a chassis and nearly identical bodywork with its counterpart (with the exception of its standard steel wheels, the Century was styled with a more upright grille than the Regal), the Century featured less powerful engines and softer suspension tuning.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In further contrast to the Regal, the Century was fitted with a full-width bench seat and a column shifter (bucket seats and a console were optional); in place of full instrumentation, the dashboard lacked a tachometer.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Offered solely as a four-door sedan (the Century Estate station wagon was discontinued), the Century carried over the standard "Custom" and upgraded "Limited" trims from the previous generation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Following the retirement of the Skylark, the Century became the entry-level line for the entire Buick brand for 1999.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 2003, the Century underwent some revision, as both trim lines were consolidated into an unnamed model.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A slight de-contenting of the model line began, with many Limited-trim features (antilock brakes, OnStar, side airbags, rear window antenna, cassette player) became optional, with the "Century" nameplate on the doors deleted (remaining only on the taillamps).
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 2005, a Special Edition option package included dual-zone automatic climate control, 16-inch chrome-plated aluminum wheels, touring tires, anti-lock brakes, a chrome grille with revised tri-shield and a rear Special Edition emblem.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] Only four exterior colors were offered with the Special Edition option package, Sterling Silver Metallic, Cashmere Metallic, Cardinal Red Metallic and Glacier Blue Metallic.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] For 2005, the Buick LaCrosse was introduced to replace both the Century and the Regal on the W-body platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] After outliving the Regal by a model year, the final Buick Century was assembled at Oshawa Car Assembly on October 25, 2004.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Buick Century was produced in China as the New Century from 1998 to 2000.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The engine was the 3.0 liter *LW9* V6 engine which was also used in the first-generation Buick GL8.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] A four-cylinder model was also available paired with a 5-speed manual gearbox.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] The Century was replaced by the Buick Regal due to poor sales.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] After the discontinuation of the model in 2000, the New Century name was used as a trim level of the Buick Regal, sold until at least 2005.
[src:chrysler-e-class/buick-century] In China, the fourth generation Buick GL8 minivan was marketed as the Buick Century.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] There are many types of car body styles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] They vary depending on intended use, market position, location, and the era they were made.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Lightweight off-road vehicle with sparse bodywork.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Originally two- or four-wheeled carriages in the 19th and early 20th centuries pulled by one horse, the motorized buggies were developed in the 1960s and grew in popularity and diversity.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A convertible allows an open-air driving experience, with the ability to provide a roof when required.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Most convertible roofs are either a folding textile soft-top or a retractable metal roof.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Convertibles with a metal roof are sometimes called 'retractable hardtop', 'coupé convertible', or 'coupé cabriolet'.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Two-door car, seating up to four persons.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Some two-door cars have only two seats, thus **two-seaters**.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Type of SUV with a sloping roofline similar to fastback cars, That is often adopted to offer a styling advantage compared to standard SUVs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Manufacturers often sell them as more premium models than their standard SUV counterparts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Vehicle with a higher ground clearence and larger space, That is built in a unibody platform shared with standard cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Originally a North American term used for vehicles that blend characteristics between two types, it evolved to be a term for SUVs built in a unibody chassis, Even though the term SUV is used to refer both to crossovers and standard SUVs due to their visual similarities.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Car with a roofline that slopes continuously down at the back.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The design features a single unbroken convex curve from the roof to the rear.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Used in the U.S. in the funeral industry to carry flowers for burial services.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Typically a coupé-style, forward-passenger compartment with an open well in the rear.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Car with a hatch-type rear door that is hinged at the roof and opens upwards.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The term "hatchback" can also refer to that type of rear door, which is also used on several sports cars, SUVs, and large luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The modification of a passenger car to provide a long cargo area for carrying a coffin or casket.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Hearses often have large glass panels for viewing the coffin.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A vehicle that combines characteristics and styling of a sedan with a higher ground clearance, Similar to a crossover.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A Kammback is a car where the rear slopes downwards before being abruptly cut off with a vertical or near vertical surface.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] This reduces the aerodynamic drag, improving the efficiency, while the stil keeping its traditional shape.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Variant of a hatchback where the roof line and the rear cargo door are more horizontal than vertical.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A luxury-type vehicle that is typically driven by a chauffeur with a partition between the driver's compartment and the passenger's compartment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Limousines may also be stretched to provide more room in the rear passenger compartment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] In some European usage, the word describes a regular four-door sedan body style.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Vehicle designed to transport passengers in the rear seating row(s) with reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Typically has a combined passenger and cargo area, a high roof, a flat floor, a sliding door for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] In Europe, some small minivans have been marketed as 'leisure activity vehicles'.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Car with a distinct rear section, With the back of the passenger compartment being in an angle to the top of what is generally the baggage compartment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A cargo vehicle based upon passenger car chassis and typically has one row of seats with no side windows at the rear.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A panel van is smaller than a panel truck or cargo van and is often built on a car platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A panel truck is a larger version of the panel van and is often built on a heavier platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] In South Africa, a pickup truck is called a "bakkie".
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] An open two-seat car with emphasis on sporting appearance or character.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Initially, an American term for a two-seat car with no weather protection, usage has spread internationally and has evolved to include two-seat convertibles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] These form separate compartments for engine, passenger, and cargo.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A sedan is called a "berlina" in Spanish and Italian, or a "berline" in French.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Initially, a horse-drawn vehicle used to carry shooting parties with their equipment and game; subsequently synonymous with station wagon / estate car; and in contemporary usage a three- or five-door wagon combining features of a station wagon and a coupé.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Type of vehicle that combines characteristics of a passenger car with a offroad vehicle, like higher ground clearence and four wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Has a two-box design, a large cargo area, and a rear tailgate that is hinged to open for access to the cargo area.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The body style is similar to a hatchback car; however, station wagons are longer and are more likely to have the roofline extended to the rear of the car (resulting in a vertical rear surface to the car) to maximize the cargo space.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] In French, a station wagon is called a "break".
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A semi-convertible style used on some sports cars, featuring a fully removable soft or hard roof panel that leaves the A and B pillars in place on the car body.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Based on a passenger sedan chassis and has a cargo tray in the rear integrated with the passenger body (as opposed to a pickup truck, which has a separate cargo tray).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] In Australia, the term "ute" was originally used solely for coupé utility cars; however, in recent years, it has also been used for pickup trucks.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Has two rows of raised seats, similar to horse-drawn carriages; usually did not have front doors, a roof, or a windshield.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The baquet ("bathtub") style was produced in the early 1900s in Europe.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Also a marketing term used on cars built in the United States in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Italian two-seat sports car with either an open-top or convertible roof.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The term was originally used for lightweight open-top racing cars from the late 1940s through the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Since the 1950s, the name barchetta ("little boat" in Italian) has been revived on several occasions, mostly for cars with convertible roofs that are not specifically intended for racing.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Italian sports coupé, typically with two seats but also including 2+2 cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A retractable textile roof, similar to a convertible/cabriolet.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The difference is that where a convertible often has the B-pillar, C-pillar, and other bodywork removed, the cabrio-coach retains all bodywork to the top of the door frames and just replaces the roof skin with a retractable fabric panel.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Some modern cars, Like the Fiat 500 (2007), featured this body style.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] An external or open-topped driver's position and an enclosed compartment for passengers.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Although the different terms may have once had specific meanings for certain car manufacturers or countries, the terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Some coupé de villes have the passengers separated from the driver in a fully enclosed compartment, while others have a canopy for the passengers and no partition between the driver and the passengers (therefore passengers enter the compartment via the driver's area).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Usually describes pillarless hardtops that are cars without a B-pillar often styled to give the appearance of a convertible.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Popular in the United States from the mid 1950s through the mid 1970s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] It also refers to a separate top that is removable and made of metal or other hard material for sports cars or small SUVs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A car where the rear passengers are covered by a convertible top.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Often the driver is separated from the rear passengers with a partition, as per a limousine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] American luxury coupés and convertibles produced from 1952 to 2007.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] An open-roof automobile without any fixed weather protection, which was popular from the 1900s until the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] An open-topped roadster body and a rear cargo bed.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A light, inexpensive, open car with basic bodywork and no windshield, top, or doors.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Most runabouts had just a single row of seats, providing seating for two passengers.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] Body style was a type of automobile body used from 1908 until the mid-1930s, which had a streamlined profile and a folding or detachable soft top.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The design consists of a hood or bonnet line raised to be level with the car's waistline, resulting in a straight beltline from front to back.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] A style of open car built in the United States that seats four or more people.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-body-style] The style was popular from the early 1900s to the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Governments and private organizations have developed **car classification** schemes that are used for various purposes including regulation, description, and categorization of cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The International Standard ISO 3833-1977 *Road vehicles – Types – Terms and definitions* also defines terms for classifying cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The following table summarises the commonly used terms of market segments and legal classifications.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Microcars and their Japanese equivalent— kei cars— are the smallest category of automobile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Microcars straddle the boundary between car and motorbike, and are often covered by separate regulations from normal cars, resulting in relaxed requirements for registration and licensing.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Engine size is often 700 cc (43 cu in) or less, and microcars have three or four wheels.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Microcars are most popular in Europe, where they originated following World War II.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The predecessors to micro cars are voiturettes and cycle cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Kei cars have been used in Japan since 1949.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The smallest category of vehicles that are registered as normal cars is called A-segment in Europe, or "city car" in Europe and the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency defines this category as "minicompact." However, this term is not widely used.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The equivalents of A-segment cars have been produced since the early 1920s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, the category increased in popularity in the late 1950s when the original Fiat 500 and BMC Mini were released.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The next larger category of small cars is called B-segment in Europe, supermini in the United Kingdom and subcompact in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The size of a subcompact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of between 85–99 cubic feet (2,410–2,800 L).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Since the EPA's smaller minicompact category is not as commonly used by the general public, A-segment cars are sometimes called subcompacts in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In Europe and Great Britain, the B-segment and supermini categories do not have any formal definitions based on size.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Early supermini cars in Great Britain include the 1977 Ford Fiesta and Vauxhall Chevette.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In the United States, the first locally-built subcompact cars were the 1970 AMC Gremlin, Chevrolet Vega, and Ford Pinto.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The largest category of small cars is called *C-segment* or *small family car* in Europe, and *compact car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The size of a compact car is defined by the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), as having a combined interior and cargo volume of 100–109 cu ft (2.8–3.1 m3).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In Europe, the third-largest category for passenger cars is called *D-segment* or *large family car*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In the United States, the equivalent term is *mid-size* or *intermediate* cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) defines a mid-size car as having a combined passenger and cargo volume of 110–119 cu ft (3.1–3.4 m3).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In Europe, the second-largest category for passenger cars is E-segment / executive car, which are usually luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In other countries, the equivalent terms are *full-size car* or *large car*, which are also used for relatively affordable large cars that are not considered luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Minivan is an American car classification for vehicles that are designed to transport passengers in the rear seating rows, and have reconfigurable seats in two or three rows.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The equivalent terms in British English are multi-purpose vehicle (MPV), people carrier, and people mover.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Minivans are often of the "one-box" or "two-box" body configuration, high roofs, flat floors, sliding doors for rear passengers, and high H-point seating.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Mini MPV is the smallest size of MPVs and the vehicles are often built on the platforms of B-segment hatchback models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The compact MPV size class includes vehicles between the mini MPV and large MPV (minivan) sizes.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Compact MPVs remain predominantly a European phenomenon, although they are also built and sold in many Latin American and Asian markets.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The largest size of minivans is also referred to as "large MPV" and became popular following the introduction of the 1984 Renault Espace and Dodge Caravan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Since the 1990s, the smaller compact MPV and mini MPV sizes of minivans have also become popular.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] If the term "minivan" is used without specifying a size, it usually refers to a large MPV.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The premium compact class (also called subcompact executive) is the smallest category of luxury cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] It became popular in the mid-2000s, when European manufacturers — such as Audi, BMW, and Mercedes-Benz — introduced new entry-level models that were smaller and cheaper than their compact executive models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A compact executive car or a compact luxury car is a premium car larger than a *premium compact* and smaller than an *executive car*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Compact executive cars are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In North American terms, close equivalents are "luxury compact" and "entry-level luxury car", although the latter is also used for the smaller *premium compact cars*.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] An executive car is a premium car larger than a *compact executive* and smaller than a *full-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Executive cars are classified as E-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In the United States and several other countries, the equivalent categories are full-size car (not to be confused with the European category of "full-size luxury car") or *mid-size luxury* car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The largest size of a luxury car is known as a *luxury saloon* in the United Kingdom and a *full-size luxury car* in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] These cars are classified as F-segment cars in the European car classification.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Vehicles in this category are often the flagship models of luxury car brands.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Cars that prioritize handling or straight-line acceleration are called sports cars or performance cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However the term "sports car" is also sometimes used specifically for lightweight two-seat cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Sports/performance cars can either be built on unique platforms or upgraded versions of regular cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The definitions for these categories are often blurred and a car may be a member of multiple categories.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Sports cars are designed to emphasize handling, performance, or the thrill of driving.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Sports cars originated in Europe in the early 1900s, with one of the first recorded usages of the term "sports car" being in *The Times* newspaper in the United Kingdom in 1919.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Sports cars started to become popular during the 1920s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The term was originally used for two-seat roadsters (cars without fixed roofs).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, since the 1970s the term has also been used for cars with fixed roofs (which were previously considered grand tourers).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A *sports sedan* — also known as "sports saloon" — is a subjective term for a sedan/saloon car that is designed to have sporting performance or handling characteristics.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A supercar – also called an exotic car – is a loosely defined description of certain high-performance sportscars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Since the 1990s or 2000s, the term "hypercar" has come into use for the highest-performing supercars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Passenger vehicles with off-road capability or styling features are often categorized as either off-road vehicles, sports utility vehicles, or crossover SUVs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] There are no commonly agreed boundaries between these categories, and usage of the terms varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The earliest type of passenger vehicle is called an "off-roader", "four-by-four" or "four-wheel drive".
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Off-road vehicles are usually more focused on off-road capability than SUVs and crossover SUVs (often compromising their on-road ride quality or handling).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Common features of off-road vehicles are four-wheel drive, high ground clearance, a body-on-frame (separate chassis) construction and low-range gearing.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A sports utility vehicle (SUV) combines elements of road-going passenger vehicles with features from off-road vehicles, such as raised ground clearance and four-wheel drive.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] There is no common definition of an SUV, and usage varies between countries.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Some definitions claim that an SUV must be built on a light-truck chassis.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, a broader definition considers any vehicle with off-road design features as an SUV.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In some countries — such as the United States — SUVs have been classified as "light trucks", resulting in more lenient regulations compared to passenger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The predecessors to SUVs date back to military and low-volume models from the late 1930s, and the four-wheel drive station wagons / carryalls that began to be introduced in 1949.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The 1984 Jeep Cherokee (XJ) is considered to be the first SUV in the modern style.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Most SUVs produced today use unibody construction (as per passenger cars).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, in the past, many SUVs used body-on-frame construction.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A crossover SUV— also called a crossover or CUV— is a type of sports utility vehicle (SUV) that uses a unibody construction.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Crossovers are often based on a platform shared with a passenger car, as a result, they typically have better comfort and fuel economy, but less off-road capability (many crossovers are sold without all-wheel drive) than truck-based SUVs, though more so than passenger four wheels.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] There are various inconsistencies about whether vehicles are considered crossovers or SUVs, therefore the term SUV is often used as a catch-all for both crossovers and SUVs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] These classifications can be based on body style (e.g. sedan, coupe or hatchback), number of doors or seating capacity.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Government departments often create classification systems for taxation or regulating vehicle usage (e.g. vehicles that require a specific license or are restricted to certain roads).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Some jurisdictions may determine vehicle tax based upon environmental principles, such as the user pays principle.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In Australia, the Federal Chamber of Automotive Industries publishes its classifications.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A similar set of classes is used by the Canadian EPA.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The classification of a three-box vehicle (sedan) is determined by its length, while the classification of a two-box car (hatchback and SUV) or MPV is determined by its wheelbase.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In the United Kingdom, a vehicle is taxed according to the vehicle's construction, engine, weight, type of fuel, and emissions, as well as the purpose for which it is used.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] In the United States, since 2010 the Insurance Institute for Highway Safety has used a formula it developed that takes into account a combination of both vehicle footprint (length times width) and weight.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The United States National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) separates vehicles into classes by the curb weight of the vehicle with standard equipment including the maximum capacity of fuel, oil, coolant, and air conditioning, if so equipped.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The United States Federal Highway Administration has developed a classification system used for automatically calculating road use tolls.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] There are two broad categories depending on whether the vehicle carries passengers or commodities.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Vehicles that carry commodities are further subdivided by the number of axles and number of units, including both power and trailer units.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (US EPA) has developed a classification system used to compare fuel economy among similar vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Passenger vehicles are classified based on a vehicle's total interior passenger and cargo volumes.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Trucks are classified based on their gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Heavy-duty vehicles are not included in the EPA scheme.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Certain cities in the United States in the 1920s chose to exempt electric-powered vehicles because officials believed those vehicles did not cause "substantial wear upon the pavements".
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in North America.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Cars from these segments may also be sold in other countries.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to North America.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Muscle car is an American term for high-performance cars, usually rear-wheel drive and fitted with a large and powerful V8 engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The term originated for the 1960s and early 1970s special editions of mass-production cars which were designed for drag racing.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Pony car is an American class of automobile launched and inspired by the Ford Mustang in 1964.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] It broke all post-World War II automobile sales records, "creating the 'pony car' craze soon adopted by competitors." The term describes an affordable, compact, highly styled car with a sporty or performance-oriented image.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A personal luxury car is a North American market segment for premium coupé or convertible produced from 1952–2007.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] These two-door cars prioritized comfort, styling, and a high level of interior features.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Not prioritizing maximum interior space, interior volumes are equivalent size to mid-size cars and are part of the D-segment in the European car classification, and exterior dimensions can exceed F-segment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A sporting version of an affordable compact car or a subcompact car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] There is no precise definition and the description is applied for marketing purposes to a wide variety of models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Cars began to be marketed as sport compacts in the mid-1980s when it was used for option packages on American-built coupes.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Since then, it has also been used for standalone sports car models and cars imported from Europe and Asia.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, sport compacts are not restricted to just hatchback body styles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Several other segment descriptions, listed below, are used in Europe.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, the usage of the terms is mostly specific to Europe.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] A grand tourer (GT) is a car that is designed for high-speed and long-distance driving, due to a combination of performance and luxury attributes.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The most common format is a front-engine, rear-wheel-drive two-door coupé with either a two-seat or a 2+2 arrangement.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] The term derives from the Italian language phrase *gran turismo* which became popular in the English language from the 1950s, evolving from fast touring cars and streamlined closed sports cars during the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Hot hatch (shortened from hot hatchback) is a high-performance version of a mass-produced hatchback car.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, factory high-performance versions of hatchbacks have been produced since the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Front-mounted petrol engines, together with front-wheel drive, are the most common powertrain layout.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] However, all-wheel drive has become more commonly used since around 2010.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-classification] Most hot hatches are manufactured in Europe or Asia.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A **car platform** is a shared set of common design, engineering, and production efforts, as well as major components, over a number of outwardly distinct models and even types of cars, often from different, but somewhat related, marques.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] It is practiced in the automotive industry to reduce the costs associated with the development of products by basing those products on a smaller number of platforms.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] This further allows companies to create distinct models from a design perspective on similar underpinnings.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A car platform is not to be confused with a platform chassis, although such a chassis can be part of an automobile's design platform, as noted below.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A basic definition of a platform in cars, from a technical point of view, includes underbody and suspensions (with axles) — where the underbody is made of the front floor, rear floor, engine compartment, and frame (reinforcement of underbody).
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing is a product development method where different products and the brand attached share the same components.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The purpose with platform sharing is to reduce the cost and have a more efficient product development process.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The companies gain on reduced procurement costs by taking advantage of the commonality of the components.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] However, this also limits their ability to differentiate the products and imposes a risk of losing the tangible uniqueness of the product.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The companies have to make a trade-off between reducing their development costs and the degree of differentiation of the products.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing is a practice commonly employed by various brands within a corporate group.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The fundamental components of a shared platform typically include the chassis and the drive unit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing facilitates the efficient production and development of vehicles by leveraging common components across different models, thereby reducing costs and enhancing operational efficiency.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] One of the first car companies to use this product development approach was General Motors in 1908.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] General Motors used a single chassis for certain class of model across most of its brands like Chevrolet, Buick, Pontiac and Oldsmobile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Later, Chrysler Corporation would do the same for Plymouth, DeSoto and Dodge cars.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Ford followed the same principle for Ford and Mercury in US markets.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The chassis unit was common with many shared mechanical components while the exterior styling and interior trims were designed according to its individual brand and category.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Pictured below is the Nissan MS platform, where designs including 5-door hatchback, sedan, compact SUV and minivan were built on a common floor panel and many shared functional assemblies such as engine, transmission and chassis components.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Many vendors refer to this as **product or vehicle architecture**.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The concept of product architecture is the scheme by which the function of a product is allocated to physical components.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The car platform strategy has become important in new product development and in the innovation process.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The finished products have to be responsive to market needs and to demonstrate distinctiveness while – at the same time – they must be developed and produced at low cost.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Adopting such a strategy affects the development process and also has an important impact on an automaker's organizational structure.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A platform strategy also offers advantages for the globalization process of automobile firms.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Because automakers spend the majority of time and money on the development of platforms, platform sharing affords manufacturers the ability to cut costs on research and development by spreading it over several product lines.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Manufacturers are then able to offer products at a lower cost to consumers.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Additionally, economies of scale are increased, as is return on investment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Originally, a "platform" was a literally shared chassis from a previously-engineered vehicle, as in the case for the Citroën 2CV platform chassis used by the Citroën Ami and Citroën Dyane, as well as the Volkswagen Beetle frame under the Volkswagen Karmann Ghia.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] These two manufacturers made different category of vehicles under using the same chassis design at different years though the primary vehicle was still in production.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] In the United States, platform sharing has been a common practice since the 1960s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] This was when GM used the same platform in the development of the Pontiac LeMans, the Buick Skylark, the Chevrolet Chevelle, and the Oldsmobile Cutlass.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] In the 1980s, Chrysler's K-cars all wore a badge with the letter "K" to indicate their shared platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] In later stages, the "K" platform was extended in wheelbase, as well as use for several of the Corporation's different models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] In the same decade, Fiat and Saab jointly developed cars using the Type Four platform to compete with the German-dominated European executive car segment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] General Motors used similar strategies with its "J" platform that debuted in mid-1981 in four of GM's divisions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Subsequently, GM introduced its "A" bodies for the same four divisions using the same tread width/wheelbase of the "X" body platform, but with larger bodywork to make the cars seem larger, and with larger trunk compartments.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] They were popular through the 1980s, primarily.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Even Cadillac started offering a "J" body model called the Cimarron, a much gussied-up version of the other four brands' platform siblings.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A similar strategy applied to what is known as the N-J-L platform, arguably the most prolific of GM's efforts on one platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Once more, GM's four lower-level divisions all offered various models on this platform throughout the 1980s and into the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The 1988 Fiat Tipo was one of the first European cars utilizing a modular platform, also used for the Fiat Tempra.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Japanese carmakers have followed the platform sharing practice with Honda's Acura line, Nissan's Infiniti brand, and Toyota's Lexus marque, as the entry-level luxury models are based on their mainstream lineup.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] For example, the Lexus ES is essentially an upgraded and rebadged Toyota Camry.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] After Daimler-Benz merged with Chrysler, Chrysler engineers used several M-B platforms for new models including the Crossfire which was based on the M-B SLK roadster.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Other models that share platforms are the European Ford Focus, Mazda 3, and the Volvo S40.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Differences between shared models typically involve styling, including headlights, tail lights, and front and rear fascias.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Examples also involve differing engines and drivetrains.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing *may* be less noticeable now; however, it is still very apparent.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Vehicle architectures primarily consist of "under the skin" components, and shared platforms can show up in unusual places, like the Nissan FM platform-mates Nissan 350Z marketed as a sports car and Infiniti FX positioned as a SUV.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The Volkswagen A platform-mates such as the sports-oriented Audi TT and the economy-focused Volkswagen Golf also share much of their mechanical components but are visually entirely different.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Both the Volkswagen Group and Toyota have had much success building many well-differentiated vehicles from many marques, from the same platforms.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] One of the least conspicuous recent examples is the Chevy Trailblazer and Chevy SSR; both use the GMT-360 platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing allows for fewer parts for different models of vehicles and therefore the task of inventorying those parts is greatly reduced.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to cover many different market segments when a platform sharing strategy is implemented.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] They are essentially the same vehicles, but they are targeted as being in the mass-market, near luxury, and luxury vehicles segments.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design parts with fewer variation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] A byproduct of this is increased quality, which results in lower defect rates.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to design flexible platforms that can be tailored to a country's specific needs without compromising quality.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] It also allows for manufacturing standardization and improved logistics.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing allows manufacturers to build/design differentiated products faster and cheaper.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] This is possible because the development and cost of the original platform have already been paid for.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Manufacturers that practice platform sharing have the ability to create several models based on the same design but with different names.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] This leads to the public looking over certain models and cannibalized sales from competing automakers with essentially similar products.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The two elements of platforms are constant and non-constant.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] If the non-constant elements are not designed to be easily integrated into the constant elements of the platform, extensive and expensive changes will have to be made in order to make the elements compatible again.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Failure to do so negates the purpose of platform sharing in that it increases costs as opposed to reducing them.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Platform sharing has the ability to be used in too many different models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] However, in the minds of the consumers, the products may be too similar and more expensive products may be perceived to be cheaper.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] For example, the perceived value of a "luxury" brand may be not as desirable if it is too similar to a mass-market version of the same platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] Conversely, platform sharing may increase the price of the economic models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] The propensity for a higher number of recall is greatly increased with platform sharing.
[src:chrysler-e-class/car-platform] If a defect is found in one model and that model shares its platform with nine other models, the recall would be magnified by ten thus costing the manufacturer more time and money to fix.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A **chart** (sometimes known as a **graph**) is a graphical representation for data and information visualization, in which "the data is represented by symbols, such as bars in a bar chart, lines in a line chart, or slices in a pie chart".
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A chart can represent tabular numeric data, functions or some kinds of quality structure and provides different info.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Charts are often used to ease understanding of large quantities of data and the relationships between parts of the data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Charts can usually be read more quickly than the raw data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] They are used in a wide variety of fields, and can be created by hand (often on graph paper) or by computer using a charting application.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Certain types of charts are more useful for presenting a given data set than others.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] For example, data that presents percentages in different groups (such as "satisfied, not satisfied, unsure") are often displayed in a pie chart, but maybe more easily understood when presented in a horizontal bar chart.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] On the other hand, data that represents numbers that change over a period of time (such as "annual revenue from 1990 to 2000") might be best shown as a line chart.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A chart can take a large variety of forms.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] However, there are common features that provide the chart with its ability to extract meaning from data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Typically the data in a chart is represented graphically since humans can infer meaning from pictures more quickly than from text.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Thus, the text is generally used only to annotate the data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] One of the most important uses of text in a graph is the **title**.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A graph's title usually appears above the main graphic and provides a succinct description of what the data in the graph refers to.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Dimensions in the data are often displayed on **axes**.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] If a horizontal and a vertical axis are used, they are usually referred to as the x-axis and y-axis.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Each axis will have a **scale**, denoted by periodic graduations and usually accompanied by numerical or categorical indications.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Each axis will typically also have a label displayed outside or beside it, briefly describing the dimension represented.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] If the scale is numerical, the label will often be suffixed with the unit of that scale in parentheses.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] For example, "Distance traveled (m)" is a typical x-axis label and would mean that the distance traveled, in units of meters, is related to the horizontal position of the data within the chart.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Within the graph, a **grid** of lines may appear to aid in the visual alignment of data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] The grid can be enhanced by visually emphasizing the lines at regular or significant graduations.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] The emphasized lines are then called major gridlines, and the remainder is minor grid lines.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A chart's data can appear in all manner of formats and may include individual textual **labels** describing the datum associated with the indicated position in the chart.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] The data may appear as dots or shapes, connected or unconnected, and in any combination of colors and patterns.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] In addition, inferences or points of interest can be overlaid directly on the graph to further aid information extraction.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] When the data appearing in a chart contains multiple variables, the chart may include a **legend** (also known as a **key**).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] A legend contains a list of the variables appearing in the chart and an example of their appearance.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] This information allows the data from each variable to be identified in the chart.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] Some specific charts have become well known by effectively explaining a phenomenon or idea.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] There are dozens of other types of charts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] While charts can be drawn by hand, computer software is often used to automatically produce a chart based on entered data.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chart] For examples of commonly used software tools, see List of charting software.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The **Chrysler E Class** is a mid-size car that was produced by Chrysler from 1983 to 1984.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Taking its name from its Chrysler platform designation, the E Class commenced an era of downsized Chrysler vehicles, serving as a companion model for the first front-wheel drive Chrysler New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Alongside the twelfth-generation New Yorker, the E Class shared the Chrysler E platform with the Dodge 600 and the Plymouth Caravelle (initially sold by Chrysler Canada).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] For its entire production, Chrysler assembled the E Class in its Jefferson Avenue Assembly facility (Detroit, Michigan).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] In launching the E Class, Chrysler introduced its first front-wheel drive cars larger than its K-Cars, as its R and M-platform cars were far larger than the mid-size segment.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Along with the New Yorker adopting the new chassis, the E Class inherited the role of the long-running Chrysler Newport; sharing its body with the New Yorker, the model line was slotted between the K-car LeBaron and the M-body Fifth Avenue in size.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] While Ford would not produce a mid-size sedan with front-wheel drive until the 1986 Taurus/Sable, Chrysler targeted the E Class against the Buick Century and Oldsmobile Cutlass Ciera (among the best-selling model lines for each brand).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Originally intended to be named the "Chrysler Grand LeBaron", the E Class name (styled without the hyphen, in contrast to Mercedes-Benz) was selected instead, in deference to its E platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The Chrysler E Class utilizes the Chrysler E platform (E=extended), which increases the K platform wheelbase 2.8 inches (from 100.3 to 103.1 inches).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Carrying over the majority of its chassis design from the K platform, the E Class is fitted with a MacPherson front strut suspension and rear trailing arms with a coil-sprung rear beam axle.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Along with cast-alloy wheels, an upgraded sport suspension was available as a stand-alone option.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The standard engine was a 2.2 L I4 (producing 94 hp) and a Mitsubishi-sourced 2.6 L I4 (producing 92 hp, with increased torque); a 3-speed automatic transmission was paired to both engines.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] For 1984, the engine lineup was revised, with the 2.2 L engine replacing its carburetor with electronic fuel injection (increasing output to 99 hp); the 2.6 L I4 was retuned (producing 100 hp).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] As a new option, a turbocharged version of the 2.2L engine was released (producing 140 hp).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Alongside its extended wheelbase, the E Class grew approximately 6 inches in length over the LeBaron (though far shorter than the Fifth Avenue).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Sharing its roofline with the Dodge 600 and Plymouth Caravelle, the E Class was offered solely as a four-door sedan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] To distinguish itself from its Dodge/Plymouth counterparts, the E-Class shared its front and rear fascias with the Chrysler LeBaron; the New Yorker was fitted with a padded vinyl roof (covering its C-pillar windows).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] For 1984, the exterior underwent a minor update, with the flat taillamps replaced by a wraparound design (shared with the LeBaron).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The interior of the E Class shared design commonality with the New Yorker (though with different trim).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] For its production, the E Class was sold in a single trim, with options either packaged together or offered individually, allowing the model line to be equipped both quite spartanly or essentially equivalent to a New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] Following slow sales of the model line (outsold nearly two-to-one by the New Yorker for 1984), Chrysler dropped the E Class from its model line for 1985.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The same car made its return to Chrysler-Plymouth dealer networks, as Chrysler repackaged it as the Plymouth Caravelle (previously sold only in Canada).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The 1985 Caravelle inherited its design from its Canadian namesake, adopting the front fascia of the Dodge 600 (with an eggcrate grille); a 1986 update adopted the front bodywork of the Chrysler LeBaron (with its own grille).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] The E platform New Yorker remained in production into the 1988 model year, fitted with a modified version of the front bodywork of the 1983-1984 E Class.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-e-class] After 1988, Chrysler replaced its E platform model lines with the AC platform (alongside the Y platform, the largest sedan variants of the K-car chassis).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The original Chrysler Corporation was founded in 1925 by Walter Chrysler from the remains of the Maxwell Motor Company.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1998, it merged with Daimler-Benz, which renamed itself DaimlerChrysler but in 2007 sold off its Chrysler stake.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company operated as Chrysler LLC through 2009, then as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2014, it was acquired by Fiat S.p.A.; it subsequently operated as a subsidiary of the new Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), then as a subsidiary of Stellantis, the company formed from the 2021 merger of FCA and PSA Group (Peugeot Société Anonyme).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] After founding the company, Walter Chrysler used General Motors (GM)'s brand diversification and hierarchy strategy that he knew of when he worked at its Buick division.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] He then acquired Fargo Trucks and the Dodge Brothers Company, and created the Plymouth and DeSoto brands in 1928.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Facing postwar declines in market share, productivity, and profitability, as GM and Ford were growing, Chrysler borrowed $250 million in 1954 from Prudential Insurance to pay for expansion and updated car designs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler expanded into Europe by taking control of French, British, and Spanish auto companies in the 1960s; but in 1978 Chrysler Europe was sold to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company struggled to adapt to changing markets, increased U.S. import competition, and safety and environmental regulation in the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It began an engineering partnership with Mitsubishi Motors, and began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On the verge of bankruptcy in the late 1970s, it was saved by $1.5 billion in loan guarantees from the U.S. government.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] New CEO Lee Iacocca was credited with returning the company to profitability in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1985, Diamond-Star Motors was created, further expanding the Chrysler-Mitsubishi relationship.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation (AMC), which brought the profitable Jeep, as well as the newly formed Eagle, brands under the Chrysler umbrella.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1998, Chrysler merged with German automaker Daimler-Benz to form DaimlerChrysler AG; the merger proved contentious with investors.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] As a result, Chrysler was sold to Cerberus Capital Management and renamed Chrysler LLC in 2007.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Like the other Big Three automobile manufacturers, Chrysler was affected by the automotive industry crisis of 2008–2010.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company remained in business through a combination of negotiations with creditors, filing for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization on April 30, 2009, and participating in a bailout from the U.S. government through the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On June 10, 2009, Chrysler emerged from the bankruptcy proceedings with the United Auto Workers pension fund, Fiat S.p.A., and the U.S. and Canadian governments as principal owners.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The bankruptcy resulted in Chrysler defaulting on over $4 billion in debts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In May 2011, Chrysler finished repaying its obligations to the U.S. government five years early, although the cost to the American taxpayer was $1.3 billion.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Over the next few years, Fiat S.p.A. gradually acquired the other parties' shares.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In January 2014, Fiat acquired the rest of Chrysler from the United Auto Workers retiree health trust, making Chrysler Group a subsidiary of Fiat S.p.A.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In May 2014, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles was established by merging Fiat S.p.A. into the company.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler Group LLC remained a subsidiary until December 15, 2014, when it was renamed FCA US LLC, to reflect the Fiat-Chrysler merger.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] As a result of the merger between FCA and PSA, on 17 January 2021 it became a subsidiary of the Stellantis Group.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler company was founded by Walter Chrysler on June 6, 1925, when the Maxwell Motor Company (est.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] 1904) was re-organized into the Chrysler Corporation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company was headquartered in the Detroit enclave of Highland Park, where it remained until completing the move to its present Auburn Hills location in 1996.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler had arrived at the ailing Maxwell-Chalmers company in the early 1920s, hired to overhaul the company's troubled operations (after a similar rescue job at the Willys-Overland car company).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In late 1923, production of the Chalmers automobile was ended.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In January 1924, Walter Chrysler launched the well-received Chrysler automobile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler Six was designed to provide customers with an advanced, well-engineered car, at an affordable price.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Elements of this car are traceable to a prototype which had been under development at Willys during Chrysler's tenure The original 1924 Chrysler included a carburetor air filter, high compression engine, full pressure lubrication, and an oil filter, features absent from most autos at the time.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Among the innovations in its early years were the first practical mass-produced four-wheel hydraulic brakes, a system nearly completely engineered by Chrysler with patents assigned to Lockheed, and rubber engine mounts, called "Floating Power" to reduce vibration.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler also developed a wheel with a ridged rim, designed to keep a deflated tire from flying off the wheel.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] This wheel was eventually adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Maxwell brand was dropped after the 1925 model year, with the new, lower-priced four-cylinder Chryslers introduced for the 1926 year being badge-engineered Maxwells.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The advanced engineering and testing that went into Chrysler Corporation cars helped to push the company to the second-place position in U.S. sales by 1936, which it held until 1949.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1928, the Chrysler Corporation began dividing its vehicle offerings by price class and function.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Plymouth brand was introduced at the low-priced end of the market (created essentially by once again reworking and rebadging the Chrysler Series 50 four-cylinder model).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] At the same time, the DeSoto brand was introduced in the medium-price field.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Also in 1928, Chrysler bought the Dodge Brothers automobile and truck company and continued the successful Dodge line of automobiles and Fargo range of trucks.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] By the mid-1930s, the DeSoto and Dodge divisions would trade places in the corporate hierarchy.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Imperial name had been used since 1926 but was never a separate make, just the top-of-the-line Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] However, in 1955, the company decided to offer it as its own make/brand and division to better compete with its rivals, Lincoln and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] This addition changed the company's traditional four-make lineup to five (in order of price from bottom to top): Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and the now-separate Imperial.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On April 28, 1955, Chrysler and Philco announced the development and production of the World's First All-Transistor car radio.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The all-transistor car radio, Mopar model 914HR, developed and produced by Chrysler and Philco, was a $150 option on the 1956 Imperial automobile models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Philco began manufacturing this radio in the fall of 1955 at its Sandusky Ohio plant.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On September 28, 1957, Chrysler announced the first production electronic fuel injection (EFI), as an option on some of its new 1958 car models (Chrysler 300D, Dodge D500, DeSoto Adventurer, Plymouth Fury).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The first attempt to use this system was by American Motors on the 1957 Rambler Rebel.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Bendix Corporation's Electrojector used a transistor "computer brain" modulator box, but teething problems on pre-production cars meant very few cars were made.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The EFI system in the Rambler ran fine in warm weather, but suffered hard starting in cooler temperatures and AMC decided not to use this EFI system on its 1957 Rambler Rebel production cars that were sold to the public.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler also used the Bendix "Electrojector" fuel injection system and only around 35 vehicles were built with this option, on its 1958 production-built car models.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Owners of EFI Chryslers were so dissatisfied that all but one were retrofitted with carburetors (while that one has been completely restored, with original EFI electronic problems resolved).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Valiant was also introduced for the 1960 model year as a distinct brand.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In the U.S. market, Valiant was made a model in the Plymouth line for 1961 and the DeSoto make was discontinued in 1961.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] With those exceptions per applicable year and market, Chrysler's range from lowest to highest price from the 1940s through the 1970s was Valiant, Plymouth, Dodge, DeSoto, Chrysler, and Imperial.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1954, Chrysler was the exclusive provider of its Hemi V8 engine in the Facel Vega, a French coachbuilder that offered its own line of hand-built luxury performance cars, coupled with the PowerFlite and TorqueFlite automatic transmissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Facel Vega Excellence was a four-door hardtop with rear-hinged coach doors that listed for US$12,800 ($142,837 in 2025 dollars ).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1960 Facel Vega introduced the smaller Facellia sports car to capitalize on its sales success with Chrysler supplied engines.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] At the time, Chrysler didn't produce a four-cylinder engine, and the company had to find alternatives before production began.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] From 1963 through 1969, Chrysler increased its existing stakes to take complete control of the French Simca, British Rootes, and Spanish Barreiros companies, merging them into Chrysler Europe in 1967.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In the 1970s, an engineering partnership was established with Mitsubishi Motors, and Chrysler began selling Mitsubishi vehicles branded as Dodge and Plymouth in North America.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler struggled to adapt to the changing environment of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] When consumer tastes shifted to smaller cars in the early 1970s, particularly after the 1973 oil crisis, Chrysler could not meet the demand, although its compact models on the "A" body platform, the Dodge Dart and Plymouth Valiant, had proven economy and reliability and sold very well.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Additional burdens came from increased US import competition, and tougher government regulation of car safety, fuel economy, and emissions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] As the smallest of the Big 3 US automakers, Chrysler lacked the financial resources to meet all of these challenges.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] 1975 would be the last year for Imperial, except for an ill-fated attempt at revival in 1981-1983, for its low sales no longer justified it as a separate brand when it didn't offer much over a high-end Chrysler New Yorker.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1976, with the demise of the reliable Dart/Valiant, quality control declined.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Their replacements, the Dodge Aspen and Plymouth Volare, were comfortable and had good roadability, but owners soon experienced major reliability problems which crept into other models as well.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Engines failed and/or did not run well, and premature rust plagued bodies.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1978, Lee Iacocca was brought in to turn the company around, and in 1979 Iacocca sought US government help.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Congress later passed the *Loan Guarantee Act* providing $1.5 billion in loan guarantees.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Also in 1978, Iacocca offloaded the ailing European operation to PSA Peugeot Citroën for a nominal $1, taking with it the group's substantial losses and debts which had been dragging the rest of the business down.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler returned to profitability in 1980, repaying the loans with interest in 1983.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Omni/Horizon were first offered with four-cylinder engines provided by Chrysler Europe brand Simca, then Volkswagen, until the all-new Chrysler engineered Chrysler K engine arrived.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler had not manufactured a four-cylinder engine since 1933 when the Chrysler flathead four-cylinder was canceled.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In November 1983, the Dodge Caravan/Plymouth Voyager was introduced, built on a modified K platform, establishing the minivan as a major category, and initiating Chrysler's return to stability.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1985, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors Corporation to produce Chrysler M platform rear-drive, as well as Dodge Omnis front wheel drive cars, in AMC's Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1987, Chrysler acquired the 47% ownership of AMC that was held by Renault.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The remaining outstanding shares of AMC were bought on the NYSE by August 5, 1987, making the deal valued somewhere between US$1.7 billion and US$2 billion, depending on how costs were counted.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted the Jeep brand, particularly the Jeep Grand Cherokee (ZJ) that was under development, the new world-class manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, and AMC's engineering and management talent that became critical for Chrysler's future success.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler established the Jeep/Eagle division as a "specialty" arm to market products distinctly different from the K-car-based products with the Eagle cars targeting import buyers.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Former AMC dealers sold Jeep vehicles and various new Eagle models, as well as Chrysler products, strengthening the automaker's retail distribution system.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Eurostar, a joint venture between Chrysler and Steyr-Daimler-Puch, began producing the Chrysler Voyager in Austria for European markets in 1992.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1998, Chrysler and its subsidiaries entered into a partnership dubbed a "merger of equals" with German-based Daimler-Benz AG, creating the combined entity DaimlerChrysler AG.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] To the surprise of many stockholders, Daimler acquired Chrysler in a stock swap before Chrysler CEO Bob Eaton retired.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Under DaimlerChrysler, the company was named DaimlerChrysler Motors Company LLC, with its U.S. operations generally called "DCX".
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Eagle brand was retired soon after Chrysler's merger with Daimler-Benz in 1998 Jeep became a stand-alone division, and efforts were made to merge the Chrysler and Jeep brands as one sales unit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2001, the Plymouth brand was also discontinued.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Eurostar also built the Chrysler PT Cruiser in 2001 and 2002.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Austrian venture was sold to Magna International in 2002 and became Magna Steyr.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Voyager continued in production until 2007, whereas the Chrysler 300C, Jeep Grand Cherokee, and Jeep Commander were also built at the plant from 2005 until 2010.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On May 14, 2007, DaimlerChrysler announced the sale of 80.1% of Chrysler Group to American private equity firm Cerberus Capital Management, L.P., thereafter known as Chrysler LLC, although Daimler (renamed as Daimler AG) continued to hold a 19.9% stake.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The economic collapse during the 2008 financial crisis pushed the company to the brink.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On April 30, 2009, the automaker filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection to be able to operate as a going concern, while renegotiating its debt structure and other obligations, which resulted in the corporation defaulting on over $4 billion in secured debts.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The U.S. government described the company's action as a "prepackaged surgical bankruptcy".
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On June 10, 2009, substantially all of Chrysler's assets were sold to "New Chrysler", organized as Chrysler Group LLC.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The federal government provided support for the deal with US$8 billion in financing at nearly 21%.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Under CEO Sergio Marchionne, "World Class Manufacturing" or WCM, a system of thorough manufacturing quality, was introduced and several products were re-launched with quality and luxury.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Ram, Jeep, Dodge, SRT, and Chrysler divisions were separated to focus on their own identity and brand, and 11 major model refreshes occurred in 21 months.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The PT Cruiser, Nitro, Liberty and Caliber models (created during DCX) were discontinued.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On May 24, 2011, Chrysler repaid its $7.6 billion loans to the United States and Canadian governments.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The US Treasury, through the Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP), invested $12.5 billion in Chrysler and recovered $11.2 billion when the company shares were sold in May 2011, resulting in a $1.3 billion loss.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On July 21, 2011, Fiat bought the Chrysler shares held by the US Treasury.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The purchase made Chrysler foreign-owned again, this time as the luxury division.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Chrysler 300 was badged Lancia Thema in some European markets (with additional engine options), giving Lancia a much-needed replacement for its flagship.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On January 21, 2014, Fiat bought the remaining shares of Chrysler owned by the VEBA worth $3.65 billion.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Several days later, the intended reorganization of Fiat and Chrysler under a new holding company, Fiat Chrysler Automobiles (FCA), together with a new logo were announced.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The most challenging launch for this new company came immediately in January 2014 with a completely redesigned Chrysler 200.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The vehicle's creation is from the completely integrated company, FCA, executing from a global compact-wide platform.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On December 16, 2014, Chrysler Group LLC announced a name change to FCA US LLC.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On January 12, 2017, FCA shares traded at the New York Stock Exchange lost value after the EPA accused FCA US of using emissions cheating software to evade diesel-emissions tests, however the company countered the accusations, and the chairman and CEO Sergio Marchionne sternly rejected them.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The following day, shares rose as investors played down the effect of the accusations.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Analysts gave estimates of potential fines from several hundred million dollars to $4 billion, although the likelihood of a hefty fine was low.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Senior United States Senator Bill Nelson urged the FTC to look into possible deceptive marketing of the company's diesel-powered SUVs.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Shares dropped 2.2% after the announcement.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] FCA US would in 2022, plead guilty to a criminal charge of conspiring to defraud the US, to wire fraud, and to violate the Clean Air Act.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On July 21, 2018, Sergio Marchionne stepped down as chairman and CEO for health reasons, and was replaced by John Elkann and Michael Manley, respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It was again fined for the 2017 model year for not meeting the minimum domestic passenger car standard.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company was also to pay affected consumers up to $280 million and offer extended warranties on such vehicles worth $105 million.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The total value of the settlement was about $800 million, though FCA did not admit liability, and it did not resolve an ongoing criminal investigation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On December 21, 2020, the European Commission approved the merger between FCA and PSA Group with minimal conditions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Shareholders approved the deal on January 4, 2021, and the merger was finalized on January 16, 2021, with FCA US now part of a new entity: Stellantis.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Stellantis shares began trading under the symbol “STLA” on the Milan Stock Exchange and Euronext Paris on January 18, followed by the New York Stock Exchange on January 19, and on the New York Stock Exchange on 19 January.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] For accounting purposes, PSA was designated the acquirer, and financial statements reflect PSA's historical performance.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Under Carlos Tavares' leadership, Stellantis faced growing criticism over its cost-cutting strategy, declining sales, and strained relations with key stakeholders.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Tavares implemented aggressive restructuring measures, including job cuts and strict control over product development, which some analysts blamed for delays in launching new models and weakening brand performance, particularly at Stellantis North America.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] U.S. dealers expressed concern about rising inventories and brand mismanagement, while the United Auto Workers criticized the company over job cuts and halted investment plans.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2024, Stellantis reported a 70% drop in net profit, with global shipments and U.S. market share declining significantly.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Amid internal friction with the board and worsening financial performance, Tavares resigned in December 2024, two years before his contract was set to expire.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On May 28, 2025, the board of Stellantis unanimously appointed Antonio Filosa, a longtime executive who had led Stellantis operations in North and South America, as CEO starting June 23.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Filosa is expected to place renewed emphasis on the North American market.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] However, the majority of its management team remains based in Europe.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Following the appointment of Filosa, formerly COO of Stellantis North America, Stellantis announced on June 10, 2025, that he would be based in Auburn Hills, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] His predecessor, Carlos Tavares, former CEO of PSA, was based in Europe and regularly worked remotely from his Portuguese property.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] He was considered by some to have insufficient presence in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On October 14, 2025, Stellantis announced an investment of $13 billion to strengthen its growth in the United States over the next four years.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company claims this is its largest investment in its century-long history in the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Belvidere, Illinois, plant will reopen for production of two new Jeep Cherokee and Jeep Compass vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company also said it will create more than 5,000 manufacturing jobs in four Midwestern U.S. states.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] On May 20, 2026, Stellantis and British luxury carmaker Jaguar Land Rover signed a memorandum of understanding to "explore synergies in areas such as product and technology development" within the United States.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Stellantis is the smallest of the "Big Three", which also includes Ford and GM.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2020, it sold just over 1.8 million vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler was the world's 11th largest vehicle manufacturer as ranked by OICA in 2012.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Total Chrysler vehicle production was about 2.37 million that year.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The company has since become a wholly owned subsidiary and no longer reports global sales.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2007, Chrysler began to offer vehicle lifetime powertrain warranty for the first registered owner or retail lessee.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The deal covered owner or lessee in U.S., Puerto Rico, and the Virgin Islands, for 2009 model year vehicles, and 2006, 2007, and 2008 model year vehicles purchased on or after July 26, 2007.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Covered vehicles excluded SRT models, Diesel vehicles, Sprinter models, Ram Chassis Cab, Hybrid System components (including transmission), and certain fleet vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] After Chrysler's restructuring, the warranty program was replaced by five-year/100,000 mile transferable warranty for 2010 or later vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2008, as a response to customer feedback citing the prospect of rising gas prices as a top concern, Chrysler launched the "Let's Refuel America" incentive campaign, which guaranteed new-car buyers a gasoline price of $2.99 for three years.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] With the U.S. purchase of eligible Chrysler, Jeep, and Dodge vehicles, customers could enroll in the program and receive a gas card that immediately lowers their gas price to $2.99 a gallon, and keeps it there for the three years.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler plans for Lancia to codevelop products, with some vehicles being shared.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Olivier Francois, Lancia's CEO, was appointed to the Chrysler division in October 2009.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Francois plans to reestablish the Chrysler brand as an upscale brand.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In October 2009, Dodge's car and truck lines were separated, with the name "Dodge" being used for cars, minivans, and crossovers and "Ram" for light- and medium-duty trucks and other commercial-use vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2011, Chrysler unveiled its "Imported From Detroit" campaign with ads featuring Detroit rapper Eminem, one of which aired during the Super Bowl.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The campaign highlighted the rejuvenation of the entire product lineup, which included the new, redesigned, and repackaged 2011 model year 200 sedans and 200 convertibles, the Chrysler 300 sedan, and the Chrysler Town & Country minivan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] As part of the campaign, Chrysler sold a line of clothing items featuring the Monument to Joe Louis, with proceeds being funneled to Detroit-area charities, including the Boys and Girls Clubs of Southeast Michigan, Habitat for Humanity Detroit and the Marshall Mathers Foundation.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In March 2011, Chrysler Group LLC filed a lawsuit against Moda Group LLC (owner of Pure Detroit clothing retailer) for copying and selling merchandise with the "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler claimed it had notified defendant of its pending trademark application February 14, but the defendant argued Chrysler had not secured a trademark for the "Imported From Detroit" phrase.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] District Judge Arthur Tarnow ruled that Chrysler's request did not show that it would suffer irreparable harm or that it had a strong likelihood of winning its case.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Therefore, Pure Detroit's owner, Detroit retailer Moda Group LLC, can continue selling its "Imported from Detroit" products.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Tarnow also noted that Chrysler does not have a trademark on "Imported from Detroit" and rejected the automaker's argument that trademark law is not applicable to the case.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In March 2012, Chrysler Group LLC and Pure Detroit agreed to a March 27 mediation to try to settle the lawsuit over the clothing company's use of "Imported from Detroit" slogan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Pure Detroit stated that Chrysler has made false claims about the origins of three vehicles - Chrysler 200, Chrysler 300 and Chrysler Town & Country - none of which are built in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Pure Detroit also said that Chrysler's Imported From Detroit merchandise is not being made in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2012 Chrysler and Pure Detroit came to an undisclosed settlement.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler's Jefferson North Assembly, which makes the Jeep Grand Cherokee and Dodge Durango, is the only car manufacturing plant of any company remaining entirely in Detroit (General Motors operates a plant that is partly in Detroit and partly in Hamtramck).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2011, Eminem settled a lawsuit against Audi alleging the defendant had ripped off the Chrysler 300 Super Bowl commercial in the Audi A6 Avant ad.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Again in 2012, Chrysler advertised during the Super Bowl.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Its two-minute February 5, 2012 Super Bowl XLVI advertisement was titled "Halftime in America".
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The ad drew criticism from several leading U.S. conservatives, who suggested that its messaging implied that President Barack Obama deserved a second term and, as such, was political payback for Obama's support for the federal bailout of the company.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Asked about the criticism in a *60 Minutes* interview with Steve Kroft, Sergio Marchionne responded "just to rectify the record I paid back the loans at 19.7% Interest.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] I don't think I committed to do to a commercial on top of that" and characterized the Republican reaction as "unnecessary and out of place".
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] First introduced as MyGig, Chrysler Uconnect is a system that brings interactive ability to the in-car radio and telemetric-like controls to car settings.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] As of mid-2015, it was installed in hundreds of thousands of Fiat Chrysler vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It connects to the Internet via the mobile network of AT&T, providing the car with its own IP address.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Internet connectivity using any Chrysler, Dodge, Jeep or Ram vehicle, via a Wi-Fi "hot-spot", is also available via Uconnect Web.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] According to Chrysler LLC, the hotspot range extends approximately 100 feet (30 m) from the vehicle in all directions, and combines both Wi-Fi and Sprint's 3G cellular connectivity.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Uconnect is available on several current and was available on several discontinued Chrysler models including the current Dodge Dart, Chrysler 300, Aspen, Sebring, Town and Country, Dodge Avenger, Caliber, Grand Caravan, Challenger, Charger, Journey, Nitro, and Ram.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In July 2015, IT security researchers announced a severe security flaw assumed to affect every Chrysler vehicle with Uconnect produced from late 2013 to early 2015.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It allows hackers to gain access to the car over the Internet, and in the case of a Jeep Cherokee was demonstrated to enable an attacker to take control not just of the radio, A/C, and windshield wipers, but also of the car's steering, brakes and transmission.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler published a patch that car owners can download and install via a USB stick, or have a car dealer install for them.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Division that manufactured bearings and gears.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Division that built inboard, outboard engines, and various types of boats.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Desoto trucks were built and sold by Chrysler in Turkey until 1978, after which Askam took over the Turkish rights to the marque.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Name derived from the AMC Eagle model after Chrysler took over American Motors in 1987.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Replaced by Plymouth Trucks in the US in 1937 and folded into the Dodge Division after 1972 in Canada.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The Valiant was introduced in 1960 as a separate Chrysler brand, then was incorporated into the Plymouth line in the US starting in 1961.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1979, Chrysler, in cooperation with the United States Department of Energy, produced an experimental battery electric vehicle, the Chrysler ETV-1.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1992, Chrysler developed the Dodge EPIC concept minivan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 1993, Chrysler sold a limited-production electric minivan called the TEVan; only 56 were produced, mostly for electric utilities.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] A second generation, the EPIC (unrelated to the concept), was released in 1997 and discontinued in 1999.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler once owned the Global Electric Motorcars company, building low-speed neighborhood electric vehicles, but sold GEM to Polaris Industries in 2011.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In September 2007, Chrysler established ENVI, an in-house organization focused on electric-drive vehicles and related technologies which was disbanded by late 2009.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In August 2009, Chrysler took US$70 million in grants from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Department of Energy to develop a test fleet of 220 hybrid pickup trucks and minivans.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The first hybrid models, the Chrysler Aspen hybrid and the Dodge Durango hybrid, were discontinued a few months after production in 2008, sharing its GM-designed hybrid technology with GM, Daimler and BMW.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Chrysler was on the Advisory Council of the PHEV Research Center, and undertook a government sponsored demonstration project with Ram and minivan vehicles.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] In 2012, FCA CEO Sergio Marchionne stated that Chrysler and Fiat planned to focus primarily on alternative fuels, such as compressed natural gas and diesel, instead of hybrid and electric drivetrains for its consumer products.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Fiat Chrysler bought a total of 8.2 million megagrams of U.S. greenhouse gas emission credits from competitors including Toyota, Honda, Tesla and Nissan for the 2010, 2011, 2013, and 2014 model years.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It had the worst fleet average fuel economy among major manufacturers selling in the US from model years 2012–2023.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] The dedicated tank building division of Chrysler, this division was founded as the Chrysler Tank division in 1940, originally with the intention of providing another production line for the M2 Medium Tank, so that the U.S.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Army could more rapidly build up its inventory of the type.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] Its first plant was the Detroit Arsenal Tank Plant.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] After December 1941 and the United States' entry into the war against the Axis powers, the Tank division rapidly expanded, with new facilities such as the Tank Arsenal Proving Ground at (then) Utica, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p01] It also quickly widened the range of products it was developing and producing, including the M4 Sherman tank and the Chrysler A57 multibank tank engine.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] During World War II, essentially all of Chrysler's facilities were devoted to building military vehicles (the Jeep brand came later, after Chrysler acquired American Motors Corporation).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] They were also designing V12 and V16 hemi-engines producing 2,500 hp (1,864 kW; 2,535 PS) for airplanes, but they did not make it into production as jets were developed and were seen as the future for air travel.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] During the 1950s Cold War period, Chrysler made air raid sirens powered by its Hemi V-8 engines.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] When the Radiation Laboratory at MIT was established in 1941 to develop microwave radars, one of the first projects resulted in the SCR-584, the most widely recognized radar system of the war era.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] This system included a parabolic antenna six feet in diameter that was mechanically aimed in a helical pattern (round and round as well as up and down).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] One of Chrysler's most significant contributions to the war effort was in radar technology.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] For the final production design of this antenna and its highly complex drive mechanism, the Army's Signal Corps Laboratories turned to Chrysler's Central Engineering Office.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] There, the parabola was changed from aluminum to steel, allowing production to form using standard automotive presses.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] To keep weight down, 6,000 equally spaced holes were drilled in the face (this had no effect on the radiation pattern).
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The drive mechanism was completely redesigned, using technology derived from Chrysler's research in automotive gears and differentials.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The changes resulted in improved performance, reduced weight, and easier maintenance.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] A large portion of the Dodge plant was used in building 1,500 of the SCR-584 antennas as well as the vans used in the systems.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Army established the Ordnance Guided Missile Center (OGMC) at Redstone Arsenal, adjacent to Huntsville, Alabama.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] To form OGMC, over 1,000 civilian and military personnel were transferred from Fort Bliss, Texas.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Included was a group of German scientists and engineers led by Wernher von Braun; this group had been brought to America under Project Paperclip.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] OGMC designed the Army's first short-range ballistic missile, the PGM-11 Redstone, based on the WWII German V-2 missile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Chrysler established the Missile Division to serve as the Redstone prime contractor, setting up an engineering operation in Huntsville and for production obtaining use from the U.S.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Navy of a large plant in Sterling Heights, Michigan.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The Redstone was in active service from 1958 until 1964; it was also the first missile to test-launch a live nuclear weapon, first detonated in a 1958 test in the South Pacific.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Working together, the Missile Division and von Braun's team greatly increased the capability of the Redstone, resulting in the PGM-19 Jupiter, a medium-range ballistic missile.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] In May 1959, a Jupiter missile launched two small monkeys into space in a nose cone; this was America's first successful flight and recovery of live space payloads.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Responsibility for deploying Jupiter missiles was transferred from the Army to the Air Force; armed with nuclear warheads, they were first deployed in Italy and Turkey during the early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] In July 1959, NASA chose the Redstone missile as the basis for the Mercury-Redstone Launch Vehicle to be used for suborbital test flights of the Project Mercury spacecraft.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Three uncrewed MRLV launch attempts were made between November 1960 and March 1961, two of which were successful.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The MRLV successfully launched the chimpanzee Ham, and astronauts Alan Shepard and Gus Grissom on three suborbital flights in January, May, and July 1961, respectively.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] America's more ambitious crewed space travel plans included the design of the Saturn series of heavy-lift launch vehicles by a team headed by Wernher von Braun.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Chrysler's Huntsville operation, then designated the Space Division, became Marshall Space Flight Center's prime contractor for the first stage of the Saturn I and Saturn IB versions.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The design was based on a cluster of Redstone and Jupiter fuel tanks and Chrysler built it for the Apollo program in the Michoud Assembly Facility in East New Orleans, one of the largest manufacturing plants in the world.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] Between October 1961 and July 1975, NASA used ten Saturn Is and nine Saturn IBs for suborbital and orbital flights, all of which were successful; Chrysler missiles and boosters never suffered a launch failure.
[src:chrysler-e-class/chrysler-p02] The division was also a subcontractor which modified one of the mobile launcher platforms for use with the Saturn IB rockets using Saturn V infrastructure.
